segments.text: This is Deborah Beale, and I am interviewing Mr. Lewis Horn on the history of the Texas Engineering Experiment Station.
The date is June 13, 1984.
Introduction in here as to who you are, but I'd like to get a little background on you as to education and how you first came to A&M.
Oh, I do want that on here.
Yeah.
I'm a graduate of Kansas State University in industrial journalism, and I've done this graduate work in industrial education there.
I worked for Beach Aircraft during the war years, World War II, that is.
and for Boeing Aircraft Company.
I was a tool engineer for Leach Aircraft and an engineer project for Boeing.
Then I joined Buckminster Fuller, who was just getting underway with his

preformed house circular house that was made of metals you know aluminum and plastic and things of that kind and used a circular form to give structure and the whole house was fastened from a pole by cables and
tension rings that gave shape to the house.

And I did the technical writing work that boosted that information out to the public, the magazines, Fortune, Architectural Record, Architectural Forum, and then all the magazines of the various industries and the like
metal field or in the plastics field that would be concerned with this design.
Are you interested in all that background?
Oh, sure.
Oh, okay.
Anyway, Buckminster Fuller felt that since everybody needed housing at the end of World War II, that this was a quick way of giving housing

by utilizing all the machinery in the industrial plants that was already set up and the reservoirs of workmen were already around and letting them use the light metals and all the kind of aircraft technology, aircraft manufacturing technology to make the parts for his

circular preformed house and so it was all geared for that so that the great big cylinder, several great big cylinders would be hauled in trucks to erection sites and could be set up by mechanics rather than carpenters
in just a few days time, whereas a conventional house took many months to build.
How did you come to be at A&M?
How did I come to A&M?
Oh, pardon me.
Then I went to the University of Florida and I was, I did the
publishing and information work for them in the engineering experiment station there, University of Florida College of Engineering.
And I was there two years, then came to Texas A&M and went to work for Dean H.W.
Barlow, who is the Dean of the College of Engineering
Do you remember what year that was?
Yes, ma'am.
August 1st, 1948.
So then I published the reports.
We called them bulletins in those days.
And later we had a research report series, then a leaflet series, then a reprint series.
Slick Paper Magazine, Portland Magazine, Texas Engineering Experiment Station News.
With regard to publishing the bulletins, the legislature in setting up the Engineering Experiment Station wanted engineering information that came from research to be
sent over the state as widely as possible.
So in those days, that was one of the major functions of the engineering experiment station, to disseminate information.
And that is stated in the documents that set up the engineering experiment station.
Now, did you have a mailing list for those?
Yes.

As I recall, the mailing list included many of our libraries of the state, where the material would always be available, and the libraries, the public libraries, the big cities, and then we had governmental agencies on the mailing list too, and even

smaller libraries over the state then we the state also traded its publications with those other agencies in other states and in other words many copies were used for exchange purposes we did that for quite a number of years then farther along the way in
engine-age trimmer station.
Apparently this money was not forthcoming for sending these things out all over, so we just somewhat can, you know, revise our mailing list and send them out not so widely.
and depended on the public writing in its documents.
That was when you were saying at the news, which said what the new documents were.
Yes, yes, we reviewed them in the magazine.
Did all they have were the bulletins when you came, right?
Yes, ma'am.
Whose idea was it to start the newsletter, that little in-house?
It was Dr. Mello's idea.
to have a newsletter, and I believe it was in mimeograph form at the time.
And he sent that out for several years.
And in 1950, I established the Texas Engineering Experiment Station News.
So after we were underway with that for several years,
And he decided to discontinue the mimeograph newsletter because he thought our magazine was doing the same job and it's just wrong.
But the glossy news was your idea?
Yes, ma'am.
And did you have a lot of trouble getting it back?
Or did you just, did they say take it and run with it?
Oh, you mean get it reviewed?
Or get the money to start it?
We used local funds for that, and we never had any problems.
That was Dr. Mello's idea.
He thought that out very wisely.
He decided that there would be fewer strings attached if we just used our local money.
And in those days, we made money from fan tests, which we did for outside concerns.
made money in other ways.
I can't remember all the ways.
And that all went into our local funds.
And so I was glad we had plenty of money there, so we were able to publish this little magazine.
Our circulation was not great at first, but it went worldwide.
And we received nice comments on it.
With the magazine, it was our idea to emphasize information, actually publishing findings that could be used, not just making announcements.
telling about things that were happening or are going to be.
We actually have data and information, useful information, in these articles that the public could use, the research public or the practicing engineer or others out there in our circulation.
Anything?
Am I all right here?
Oh yeah, you're doing good.
You're giving me all sorts of... Was there anyone in charge of publications before you came?
Who did that?
Mr. W.D.
Scotts was in charge of publications, but he also ran the fan testing laboratory.
So he, but he had no background really in it, did he?
No, but he did a good job publishing it.
He just did the bulletins?
The bulletins, yes.
So yours was a new position when you came?
Yes.
And so it was, they were... And when I came, Mr. Schultz devoted his full time to the fan testing work.
So they were making a definite effort to try and increase publications when they hired you and disseminate some information.
Yes ma'am.
We put information into the newspapers and magazines, journals, write articles for journals.
And I'd help the men write articles for the technical journals.
And I'd write some myself.
And it was just interesting and fun to do all that.
In 1958, I believe it was, you wrote a historical piece for the news.
I don't know if you remember that piece or not.
Yes, I remember it.
Was that your idea, or did someone ask you to do the history?
I can't remember anybody asking me.
I think it was my idea, yes.
Was it easy to get access to people at that time?
to find out what their ideas were?
Because I noticed at the end, you said that the push now is for outside funding.
Oh, yes.
You could just walk in.
You could just walk in.
A fella like myself could just walk into any laboratory.
And we were friends, and fellas would tell me things.
And sometimes I'd ask them to write special things for me, and they would do it.

They were very cooperative, and I got interested in their work, and I would write up their work, and he would tell me all about it, and give me background information, give me some of their data, and so on, and it was fun to write up their material.
You were here when Rose was here.
Aaron Rose, yes.
Do you remember when he left, and why he left?
He was here only one year.
And I noticed, I think he was, this is a little, this might be a little bit of a guess.
I think he was here from 1958 to 1959, along in there.
I don't know why he left, really.
I didn't know if you'd uncovered that in your?
No.
But he went to California, but he later joined some corporation out there, I think.
But at the time he left, I don't believe he had a job.
In the reprints, whose idea was it to reprint?
The technical articles that were printed in other magazines?
Yes, all right.
Men like to show that they're active in their professions, so they write in their own technical journals, technical journals of their societies or the trades.
And they would submit those themselves, yes.
And if they needed help in
preparing them or submitting them, why I would help them.
They knew where they were going with those articles.
And quite often, you had researchers that had theses or dissertations that they wanted to turn into technical articles of those kinds.
And they would send those.
to the journalists.
If they needed help in sending them, I would help them.
And that worked out fine.
Then we decided to buy reprints.
So usually the technical journalists would make us a low price for a quantity of reprints, and we would buy them, and I'd put a jacket on them.
It seemed like it was a green jacket with the title in it.
And with the Engineering Experiment Station name at the bottom.
And the date and so on.
And we put a reprint number on it.
So that was the reprint series.
And what was the difference between the bulletin and
The technical report that came out that time?
Research report.
Research report.
Well...
Think about that one.
Yeah, think about that.
But...
I think with...
I guess the research report was basically a report on this particular project and what was found on the project in the research work in the laboratory or in the field.
And so its findings were presented in that format and for the specific audience it intended to reach.
which was other researchers and practitioners of that field.
The bulletins sometimes were a little more general, you know, covered a wider field, and they were on various kinds of subjects.
Some of them were rather technical and specialized, but some were of broader interest
We even published proceedings and the like in the bulletin series, proceedings of conferences.
Along the lines of those proceedings, were those conferences that were held by or sponsored at all by TEAS, or did TEAS just publish these?
No, I believe most of those were sponsored by the Engineering Experience Station.
I know they had all the highway conferences and they'd list the Civil Engineering Department and A&M, but they never did list TEAS on the bulletins.
Occasionally they would, but not always.
And I didn't know if that meant TEAS wasn't involved in the actual...
That's a hard one to answer.
I think, like you've indicated, that sometimes a group, like maybe in chemical engineering, had a conference and they wanted somebody to help them publish it.
And since we had organized facilities for publishing, I think sometimes those
came into our bulletin series.
And now the highway publications from the civil engineering department really belonged with us because some of the earliest research in the engineering experiment station involved the highways.
That was before there was even a highway department in Texas.
And we had
bulletins on the earth roads and sand clay roads and building the various kind of bridges on these country roads.
In those days the counties built the roads and then some years later
Probably five or six years after the Engineering Experiment Station became active, Texas established the Texas Highway Department.
So then you had regular highway engineers working with the roads and you had a state budget and so on.
But before, they were built by the counties.
TTI was a division of TEAS until this last couple of years, according to TEAS, but it's also been listed for years and years as a separate section of the system, the university system.
So what was the actual relationship between them?
I hope somebody doesn't take offense in administration or anything I say, because I might not be too accurate.
But the way I looked at it, we were established by the legislature.
The groundwork was laid in 1950.
But it was 1955 before we had actually had
laboratories and desks in the Texas Transportation Institute.
And I remember helping TTI out as a publisher.
I did some of their work free before they got underway too well.
research projects and needed somebody to help them publish, and I helped them publish some of the early reports.
Then later, Texas Transportation Institute materials were published by the Texas Engineering Experiment Station.
You know, through the organization of the Texas Engineering Experiment Station,
but under their own format.
And I was on one third time with the Texas Transportation Institute.
We, the Texas Transportation Institute at that time, I believe,
began handling its money through the Inchenang Experiment Station facilities.
You know, it actually handled its money through the Inchenang Experiment Station setup.
And this went on for a lot of years, and then it helped into just a few years ago.
But somewhere along the line,
Quite a good many years ago, the Texas Transportation Institute was considered to be one of the units of the system.
But when they would go over to the legislature, they'd go over alongside of the engineering experiment station.
So it was really financial that was the only connection?
Yes, the financial setup was handled
in coordination with the engineering experience station.
With the engineering experience station, I think, supervising on that.
When Rudder became president, all sorts of things changed here at the university.
What kind of impact did that have on your job?
On my job?
Yeah, on your job.
No.
Absolutely not.
He was a fine gentleman, a very good friend, yes.
What led to the end of the publications in 1963?
63, yes.
Dr. Winerdi, R. E. Winerdi, was associate director

of the Engineering Experiment Station at that time, and he decided he wanted to discontinue the Texas Transportation Institute, I mean the Texas Engineering Experiment Station News, and maybe have an annual publication of some kind, similar to a very colorful annual report.
So he asked me to discontinue the news, and of course I did.
And I think about a year later, I was transferred to the Texas Transportation Institute, and it was to give me more opportunities.
That meant salary-wise.
And so Dean Benson enabled me to make a move to the Transportation Institute, which I had been with on one-third time all along.
And this put me with the Transportation Institute full time.
By that time, the Transportation Institute
and become a full-blown foreign musician.
And I immediately started a magazine with them, the Texas Transportation Researcher.
And this goes worldwide.
We started that in 1965.
I feel that it's helped the Institute a lot in getting recognition with technologists and business people and governmental people all over the world and especially in our country.
very interesting correspondence from people we reach.
And there's an associate dean at the University of Puerto Rico, wrote me a year or two ago.
He says, I've been receiving your publication for 15 years, and I want to thank you for this fine publication and the fine work that you're doing.
He was so pleased that we made A&M's work known to him.
When you left to go to TTI, they didn't replace you, did they?
Well, the first man, I guess they brought somebody in to do the work.
They needed somebody to do the work.
Well, they didn't publish anything for the next 10 years from us.
An English professor, an assistant professor in English, handled the publications on a part-time basis, and I think he had secretarial help.
Then a young man came in and he did that for several years.
Oh, let's see, I'll turn it on.
He had been a printer in Bryan, ran a printing firm there.
He ran the operation for several years, and then a man by the name of Jay Saul came in, and he handled the information and publishing for the Texas Extension Experiment Station.
Is that when they started up the technical bulletin?
Yes, ma'am.
That was his.
All they really published for those 10 years after you left were the reports they'd send to NASA or to whoever they were doing research for.
Yes.
And it drives you crazy trying to find the history when you have to go back and there's nothing there.
That's one reason I'm doing the interviews is to try and fill in some of those gaps.
Was the printing done here on campus?
Yes, ma'am.
So you did the whole setup?
Yes, ma'am.
And did you work with anyone outside of the A&M system in terms of?
I know you were involved in conferences, because I read several times you presented papers on technical publications and that type of thing.
Were those professional conferences you'd go to?
Give me your exact question again.
I read an article that you had
presented a paper on the publication of technical reports or something along that line at a conference.
Oh, yes.
And did you get to go to a lot of those conferences?
I guess I could have gone.
I didn't go to too many.
I didn't know if this was something you got to do all the time or if this was just...
I didn't do too much of that, no.
Oh, yeah, I remember now.
That was with the American College Public Relations Association and organizations at that time.
I went to some of those conferences, and when asked to, I presented a paper, but I didn't do too much of that.
When TEAS became, or when A&M became a system,
You were here then.
Yes, ma'am.
And did that really change anything, the way things worked?
No.
You know, down here at this level, you just do your work and you just kept the work going regardless of what was happening in administration.
You made this known in your publications with the masthead and things like that, that the organization had changed a little.
And there would be news stories in there about a chancellor that had been appointed and so on.
But it never affected the work.
I guess in science and engineering
You always have this work to do.
And other things don't affect it very much.
How about changes in directors of teas?
Did that affect you much?
Not too much.
I got along with all of them, yes.
Did they all pretty much leave you alone to get your work done?
Yes, ma'am.
I mean, they seemed to appreciate what I was doing and let me do it my way.
I've always appreciated that on the part of my superiors.
They always let me do what I needed to do.
Once in a while, you know, they would point out something that they knew I'd be doing or covering and so on.
And I was always glad to do that.
When they brought in the big push for the Nuclear Science Center and all that,
I noticed for quite a few months you had lots of publications on what a nuclear reactor does and all this type of thing.
Was that part of a big publicity push by the university?
Yes, ma'am.
At that time, I was also writing all the big proposals for engineering experimentation.
And we kind of had a little corner on the proposal business because we had the facilities.
I helped write the proposal for the Nuclear Science Center and even helped the physics department with the proposal for the cyclotron, for the engineering experiment station.
And with our data processing facilities, we got the first building and then we got an expansion.
We expanded the plant later on.
And all along, like with the data processing, we kept going to better machines.
We started out with 650 way back.
Then we'd go to bigger machines until we ended up with this great big one now.
It's a nuclear science center, data processing center, cyclotron.

Like with the Nuclear Science Center, we'd help researchers in agriculture and other fields at A&M to write proposals for money because they would be using our facilities and we'd help them with the proposals.
So I'd be asking for the right things so they would be presenting their best program to those people that would be doing the financing.
And at one time, I had a whole side of a wall of shelves
filled with data sheets on almost every scientist at A&M.
You could have the data sheet there, pull it down to put in the proposal.
Sounds like a good idea.
Yeah.
And then also, sometimes the men would get so busy after they got their nuclear science, got their, you know,
reactor, they forget to write these quarterly reports that were required by the agency in Washington.
And I'd help them write those, you know.
Kind of fill in the detail a little bit, yeah.
Go in with the questions and say, okay, now I've got to fill in this blank here and this blank here.
What's the answer?
Well, mostly you wrote paragraphs on it.
what you did and how you were using the facility.
So you'd go chasing them around the facility as they were working, saying, okay, now tell me this.
Yeah, and they would, yes, and they would, the men would approve those and send them in to Washington, yes.
Now, I noticed that towards the end of the 50s,
more and more articles were being written on the highway research in there.
Was this a result of a big growth in TTI's activities in the late 50s?
Because they were established in 55.
Yes ma'am.
And did it take them a couple of years to really get going?
We went with smaller programs at first and the

highway department kept building the budgets for us and it took years to develop the budgets that we know nowadays and then somewhere along the line there was interest in the in the regional highway program and a lot of research that was done by
TTI had application in the inter-regional highway program.
And we took years to build that.
I guess it's in the late 50s, we started getting into the highway safety field and began building things to make the highways safer, especially

safer when collisions were involved and one of our first breaks was to develop a breakaway signpost and that idea is still used today and we still do breakaway research for the Federal Highway Administration and we do research to
soften the impact of vehicles striking solid objects or any kind of objects.
So we have done a lot of work with impact and attenuation devices.
How did the
energy crisis in the mid-70s affect TTI's research?
Well... Or did it?
You were...
It affected it, all right, but I... You know, our people were always energy.

conscious especially our economists and planners and they would their studies involved economics of highway operations and so on even like with highway materials you were concerned about the energy costs of
bringing aggregates from way off to a highway site and so on.
And you started doing research to provide for aggregates to be used that were close at hand by thoroughly testing those

lesser aggregates that weren't quite as satisfactory as those that we were hauling from farther away, and trying to determine whether you could actually use those, and under what conditions and so on, and what you needed to do to them.
So we were energy conscious in all our research, yes.
How did you get involved in Mr. Cotton's history of engineering?
Because you wrote the chapter on teas.
Oh, Professor Crawford's book.
Yeah, Crawford, sorry.
Oh, he just asked me to write those two chapters.
He knew who it was and would know it, huh?
Yes.
Did it take a lot of digging, or did you pretty much remember?
No, most of it I had my fingertips from working with the agencies through the years.
Did you notice while you were working there a focus in the direction TEAS was going?
Any change in that focus?
The way TEAS was going?
You know, the types of research they did?
Well, there were various kinds of
new interests always being established, and you would establish a center for that type of interest.
And that is so you could deal with the outsiders a little better.
They could find you in the maze of laboratories and people that was A&M.
And by having a center, those people could find you a lot easier.
but many of those centers started after I went over to the Institute.
Do you remember a time period that you helped write proposals for grants and things?
Do you remember a time that you felt like you were absolutely deluged with people wanting you to help them write grants and that type of thing?
Was it any different than usual?
Well, the man himself would...
initiate the proposal, and most of the time you were just helping him.
You were helping him with what he needed to do that.
And so, I didn't mean to give the impression that I was writing all the proposals.
Now the big ones, or the big facilities, a lot of people would write that.
I wrecked those and I had a party in that.
Were there any really big ones like those before the cyclotron and that type of thing?
No.
Up into the 60s, the Research Foundation, which handled those proposals, was a very small organization, just a few people.
The Research Foundation was started by Dr. A.
A. Jakula way back, and he just had a secretary.
And then they moved up into the System Building, and there were, there was a director and a business officer, and then there were several secretaries, and then
They added people, but the big,
